  "docs": {
    "CONTRIBUTING.md": "# Contributing\n\n## Setup\n```bash\npip install -e '.[dev]'\n```\n\n## Conventions\n- All business logic lives in `src/services/` — never in routes.\n- Routes validate input via validators.py before passing to services.\n- Repository layer is the only place that imports SQLAlchemy.\n- Every service method must have a corresponding test in `tests/`.\n\n## Error handling\nRaise domain-specific exceptions (`ValidationError`, `DuplicateResourceError`) in the service layer. Routes catch these and map to HTTP responses. Never raise `HTTPException` from service code.",
    "docs/adr/001-repository-pattern.md": "# ADR 001: Repository Pattern for Data Access\n\n## Status\nAccepted\n\n## Context\nEarly versions had SQLAlchemy queries scattered across service methods. This made testing hard (services needed a real DB) and made it difficult to change the ORM layer.\n\n## Decision\nAll database access goes through `src/db/repository.py`. Services depend on the repository interface, not on SQLAlchemy directly.\n\n## Consequences\n- Services can be unit-tested by mocking the repository.\n- Switching the ORM or data store only requires changes in `src/db/`.\n- The repository is the only file that may import `sqlalchemy`."
